Dr. Ray Peat mentions in the "Altitude and Mortality" article (I think citing Solco Walle Tromp) that stormy weather recreates the conditions of high altitude in allowing the body to retain more CO2. I wonder if lifting during a thunderstorm is similar to high-altitude training.

It would be fun to try to time your workouts with the weather, looking at the weather forecast and using a barometer to measure the atmospheric pressure to see when the oxygen pressure drops and carbon dioxide starts to be retained easier. Biometeorological weightlifting.

Dmitry Galkovsky had an interesting theory that the origin of royal families and popes putting numerals in their names (e.g. Charles III, Pope Pius VII, etc.) started when illiterates who did not understand Latin stumbled on Roman titular naming customs and tried to imitate them.

So instead of "John Secretary Five Times" it becomes "John Five Times". A particularly bizarre example he found was a Belgian noble family called "Vilain XIIII" (NOT "XIV", but "XIIII"). That was not a given name, but a family name. So you'd be called "John Fourteen". Cargo cult.

E.g. Octavian Augustus' full title was "Imperator Caesar Divi filius Augustus, Pontifex Maximus, Consul XIII, Imperator XXI, Tribuniciae potestatis XXXVII, Pater Patriae", meaning he was consul 13 times, granted the power of the tribune 37 times, etc. This was taken as a surname.
